Imputation with constraints

Introduction

In this work a method to correct imputed data subject to constraints is programmed in the so-called R language. It is based on the method presented in reference [1] in the section 10.11 Constrain Value Adjustment and try to extend it. Boyle-Dykstra Projection Algorithm is used.

Imputation with constraints

The object of study of this work are data sets whose variables has to satisfy some restrictions tha can be give in form of ecuations. This data set initally could have missing values which are imputed with some imputation technique (median, mean,linear regression….)

For example let be the next set, in which we have already done the imputation or initialy there were not missing values. In this DataFrame we have four individuals and three variables for each one.

x1 x2 x3
ind1 0 0 -3
ind2 1 7 0
ind3 0 1 1
ind4 2 1 3

And this data point (\(x=(x_1,x_2,x_3)\)) has to satisfy the next restrictions:

\[ \left \lbrace \begin{array}{c} x_1+x_2+x_3 \leq 1 \\ x_1+2x_2+3x_3 \leq -6 \\ x_1 \leq 3 \end{array} \right.\]

Each of this ecuations can be seen as subset \(C_i\) of the “space” to which each data point has to belong.

If a data point (\(x\)) doesn´t satisfy some ecuation (\(C_i\)) a better option can be consider other point “near” to the original but satisfaying them.

So the problem to solve can be watch as follow, for each data point (\(x_0\)) not satisfaying the restrictions \(C = \cap_i C_i\) find the “nearest” point \(x'\) that satisfy them (Best Approximation Problem):

\[ |x'-x_0| = min \{ |x-x_0|: x \in C \} \]

Where at first the restrictions \(C_i\) can be given by nonlinear equations, for example:

\[|x|\leq r^2\] (type ball restriction)

For the example data frame: \(x_1^2+x_2^2+x_3^2 \leq r^2\)

To solve this problem we use the Boyle-Dykstra Projection Algorithm, that presented below.
